ks and island beaches. Non-breeding season habitats include coastal lagoons, river mouths, and rice fields. Their nests consist of shallow scrapes in the sand. Most commonly a clutch contains 2 eggs, but the yellow-billed tern can lay anywhere between 1–4 eggs. The incubation period is approximately 24 days. Nests are usually formed very close to each other. Terns aggressively defend their nests from predators, and other species such as the sand-colored nighthawk (Chordeiles rupestris) have been known to nest among tern colonies to take advantage of this anti-predator behavior. Feeding The yellow-billed tern forages during the day, mostly on small fish, shrimp, and insects. It feeds by hovering and picking fish from surface waters. References", "shortSummary": "The yellow-billed tern (Sternula superciliaris) is a small seabird found in South America. It is a species of tern in the family Laridae.", "locations": ["路易·皮埃尔·维埃约", "玻利維亞", "哥伦比亚", "厄瓜多尔", "法屬圭亞那", "圭亚那", "巴拿马", "巴拉圭", "蘇利南", "千里達及托巴哥", "乌拉圭", "委內瑞拉"], "lat": -34.0, "lng": -64.0, "imageUrl": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b1/Yellow-billed_tern_Sternula_superciliaris.jpg/960px-Yellow-billed_tern_Sternula_superciliaris.jpg", "order": "Charadriiformes", "family": "Laridae", "genus": "Sternula", "species": "Sternula superciliaris", "orderCn": "鸻形目", "familyCn": "鸥科", "speciesCn": "Yellow-billed tern", "kingdomId": "taxonomy-kingdom-animalia", "phylumId": "taxonomy-phylum-chordata", "classId": "taxonomy-class-aves", "orderId": "taxonomy-order-charadriiformes", "familyId": "taxonomy-family-laridae", "genusId": "taxonomy-genus-sternula", "speciesId": "taxonomy-species-sternula-superciliaris", "taxonomyIds": {"kingdom": "taxonomy-kingdom-animalia", "phylum": "taxonomy-phylum-chordata", "class": "taxonomy-class-aves", "order": "taxonomy-order-charadriiformes", "family": "taxonomy-family-laridae", "genus": "taxonomy-genus-sternula", "species": "taxonomy-species-sternula-superciliaris"}, "exp